1 Description

ST_model focuses on modeling distributions of particular OTUs across the gradient. This often requires subsetting by sample type to better understand changes in abundance. Mostly making linear models.

TODO:

  • Try Generalized Additive Models for Location, Scale and Shape (GAMLSS). See https://bmcbioinformatics.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12859-019-2744-2 for comparison between GAMLSS and asin(sqrt())

  • Make lists of significant, abundant, variable otus and investigate them more thoroughly.

  • Finally, with both (1) and this last bit, another useful thing is to relate effect (x) vs.abundance (y) or fit r2 (y) and either color by p or binary black/grey depending on p<0.05. You likely will have to transform the axes to get good spread and a nice volcano. But these will help you identify bugs that respond strongly to elevation (effect on x) and are either abundant, fit tightly to elevation, and/or are significant. Wikipedia the volcano plot for some examples, or just google image search it.

2 Pick out variable OTUs

Goal: volcano plot of -log10(p-value for shore_dist) vs.shore_dist slope or the relative abundance of OTUX to identify a few choice OTUs that are both abundant/change a lot and are highly significant

2.2 Set up the model

To get started, define a function that generates linear models (lm) for each otu. Currently, the model takes zscore of otu abundance as X and zscore of distance from shore as Y.

OTUs and values for X are pulled from a phyloseq object. The model coefficients (intercept and slope) and summary coefficients (probablilities, errors, etc.) are stored in a data frame.

Might switch this over to manylm function in mvabund or gamlss for better (more complicated) model fitting.

# define a function to run linear models, output model coefficients, summary, and relative abundance
# function will also transform both dependent and independent variable to z-scores

get_z_models <- function(physeq, variable = "shore_dist", raw_abund) {
  ## Testing:
   # variable = "shore_dist"
   # physeq = ST
  # 
  # pull out variable from sample data
  shore_dist <- physeq@sam_data[[variable]] %>% as.vector
  # transform to z score
  shore_dist_z  <- scale(shore_dist, center = T, scale = T)

  # pull out otu abundances
  abund <- otu_table(physeq) %>%  as.data.frame()
  
  # apply model to each otu
  probs <- apply(abund, 1, function(x.row) {
          #TESTING: 
          #x.row = abund[1200,] %>% unlist()
          # *** MODEL DEFINITION ***
          x.row_z <- scale(x.row)
          mod1 <- lm(x.row_z ~ shore_dist_z)
          ####################################
          
          sum1 <- summary(mod1)
          
          append(sum1$coefficients, sum1$r.squared)
          
          
          }) %>%
          t() %>%
          as.data.frame()
  # set column names for model outputs
  colnames(probs) <-
  c(
  "intercept",
  "int_err",
  "int_t_value",
  "int_p",
  "slope",
  "slope_err",
  "slope_t_value",
  "slope_p",
  "r.squared"
  )
  # add otu names as a column
  probs$otu <- row.names(abund)
  # add otu relative abundance as a column
  probs$rel_abund <- rowSums(abund)/sum(rowSums(abund))
  
  # list otu abundance table and model information
  output <- list(probs,abund)
  names(output) <- c("models","abundance")
  return(output)
}

2.3 Linear models : Look for abundant OTUs that change a lot

Having run the model, how many OTUs show up as significantly associated with distance from shore? How many of those OTUs also vary in their abundance (slope of the linear regression)? How many of those OTUs are also highly abundant?

To answer these questions, define functions for two types of volcano plots:

1) p-value of OTU vs.variable slope (usually distance from shore) 2) p-value of OTU vs.relative abundance of OTU

Plots include a vertical line at p = 0.001

# Plot 1
# define a function to plot p value of otu slope vs the actual slope coefficient
plot_pval_vs_slope <- function(got_models, description)
{
  plot(
    x = got_models$models$slope,
    y = -log10(got_models$models$slope_p),
    
    main = paste(description, ": P value shore_dist slope vs. shore_dist slope"),
    xlab = "shore_dist slope",
    ylab = "p value shore_dist slope (-log10)",
  
    pch = 1,
    col = "darkblue"
    )
  abline(h = -log10(0.05))
}

# Plot 2
# define a function to plot p value of otu slope vs the relative abundance of the OTU
plot_pval_vs_RA <- function(got_models, description, physeq)
{
  plot(
    x = got_models$models$rel_abund,
    y = -log10(got_models$models$slope_p),
    
    main = paste(description, ": P value shore_dist slope vs. relative abundance"),
    xlab = "relative abundance of OTU in data",
    ylab = "p value shore_dist slope (-log10)",
    
    pch = 1,
    col = "darkred"
    )
  abline(h=-log10(0.05))
}

2.3.1 Linear models : All samples

Probably, running these models on all samples together will not be very informative, but lets try!

# run linear model on all OTUs across all samples (phyloseq object "ST")
p_all_samples <- get_z_models(physeq = ST, variable = "shore_dist")

# how many otus have a tiny p value?
length(p_all_samples$models$slope_p[  p_all_samples$models$slope_p < 0.05  ] )
## [1] 2893
# plot 1
plot_pval_vs_slope(p_all_samples, "Samples")

# plot 2
plot_pval_vs_RA(p_all_samples, "Samples")

2.4 Volcano plots

Take the model outputs and make a volcano plot. Effect size (regression coefficient) will be on x axis. Y axis can be relative abundance, or fit. Color points by p value < 0.05

# Make a basic volcano plot
  with(p_all_samples, plot(models$slope, models$slope_p, pch=20, main="Volcano plot"))

# Add colored points: red if models$slope_p<0.05, orange of log2FC>1, green if both)  
with(subset(p_all_samples$models, slope_p<.05 ), points(slope, slope_p, pch=20, col="red"))
